# Project: pytest Python Unit Test Framework

## Framework Structure
- Use pytest as the primary test runner for Python projects
- Organize tests in a dedicated tests/ directory mirroring the src/ structure
- Use pyproject.toml or pytest.ini for centralized configuration
- Separate unit, integration, and functional tests into distinct subdirectories

## Coding Standards
- Follow PEP 8 style guide with Black formatter (line length: 88)
- Use type hints for all test functions and fixtures
- Name test files with test_ prefix (test_user_service.py) or _test suffix
- Name test functions with test_ prefix describing the scenario (test_returns_none_when_not_found)

## Fixture Design
- Define shared fixtures in conftest.py at the appropriate directory level
- Use the narrowest scope possible: function (default) > class > module > session
- Prefer yield fixtures for setup/teardown to keep logic together
- Avoid returning mutable global state from session-scoped fixtures
- Parametrize fixtures when the same fixture needs multiple configurations

```python
# conftest.py
import pytest
from myapp import create_app, db as _db

@pytest.fixture(scope="session")
def app():
    app = create_app({"TESTING": True, "DATABASE_URL": "sqlite:///:memory:"})
    yield app

@pytest.fixture(scope="function")
def db(app):
    with app.app_context():
        _db.create_all()
        yield _db
        _db.drop_all()

@pytest.fixture
def user(db):
    from myapp.models import User
    u = User(email="test@example.com")
    db.session.add(u)
    db.session.commit()
    return u
```

## Test Organization
- Group related tests in classes (TestUserService) for shared fixtures and logical grouping
- Keep each test focused on a single behaviour; one assert per logical outcome
- Use descriptive names: test_create_user_raises_value_error_when_email_is_blank
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern with blank lines between sections

## Parametrize
- Use @pytest.mark.parametrize for data-driven tests instead of for-loops inside tests
- Include an ids argument for readable test names in the output
- Combine multiple @parametrize decorators for cross-product scenarios sparingly

```python
@pytest.mark.parametrize(
    ("email", "expected_error"),
    [
        ("", "Email cannot be blank"),
        ("not-an-email", "Invalid email format"),
        ("a" * 255 + "@x.com", "Email too long"),
    ],
    ids=["blank", "invalid_format", "too_long"],
)
def test_create_user_validates_email(email, expected_error):
    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=expected_error):
        User.create(email=email)
```

## Markers
- Register custom markers in pyproject.toml to avoid PytestUnknownMarkWarning
- Use built-in marks: @pytest.mark.skip, @pytest.mark.skipif, @pytest.mark.xfail
- Tag tests with domain markers (smoke, slow, integration) for selective execution
- Use @pytest.mark.usefixtures for fixtures not needed as function arguments

```toml
# pyproject.toml
[tool.pytest.ini_options]
markers = [
    "smoke: fast sanity checks run on every push",
    "slow: tests taking more than 1 second",
    "integration: require external services",
]
```

## Mocking
- Use pytest-mock's mocker fixture instead of unittest.mock.patch decorators
- Patch at the point of use, not at the definition site
- Use mocker.patch.object for instance methods; mocker.patch for module-level names
- Assert mock calls explicitly with assert_called_once_with or assert_any_call
- Restore mocks automatically — pytest-mock handles teardown per test

```python
def test_sends_welcome_email(mocker):
    send = mocker.patch("myapp.email.send_email")
    UserService.create(email="new@example.com")
    send.assert_called_once_with(to="new@example.com", subject="Welcome")
```

## Async Testing
- Install pytest-asyncio and set asyncio_mode = "auto" in pyproject.toml
- Mark async test functions with @pytest.mark.asyncio when not in auto mode
- Use anyio for framework-agnostic async fixtures
- Keep async fixtures at the appropriate scope; avoid session-scoped async fixtures with trio

## Assertions
- Use plain assert statements; pytest rewrites them for detailed failure output
- Use pytest.raises as a context manager, not with expected_exception= argument
- Match specific error messages with pytest.raises(ExcType, match=r"pattern")
- Use pytest.approx for floating-point comparisons

## Coverage
- Configure pytest-cov in pyproject.toml; run with --cov=src --cov-report=term-missing
- Set minimum thresholds with --cov-fail-under=80 in CI
- Exclude non-testable files (migrations, __init__.py) with omit patterns
- Generate HTML reports locally for visual branch-coverage analysis

```toml
[tool.coverage.run]
source = ["src"]
omit = ["*/migrations/*", "*/__init__.py"]

[tool.coverage.report]
fail_under = 80
show_missing = true
```

## Test Data Management
- Use factory_boy or polyfactory for model factories instead of hardcoded dicts
- Keep fixtures small; build only the minimum state needed for the test
- Use tmp_path fixture for tests that read/write files
- Store large static fixtures in tests/fixtures/ as JSON or YAML files

## Plugin Ecosystem
- pytest-mock: mocker fixture for clean patch/spy/stub API
- pytest-asyncio: async test and fixture support
- pytest-cov: coverage integration
- pytest-xdist: parallel execution with -n auto
- pytest-httpx or responses: mock HTTP calls without real network
- freezegun / time-machine: freeze datetime in tests

## Performance
- Run independent tests in parallel with pytest-xdist (-n auto)
- Mark slow tests and skip them in fast feedback loops (-m "not slow")
- Use session-scoped fixtures for expensive resources (database schema creation)
- Avoid importing heavy modules at collection time; import inside tests when needed

## CI/CD Integration
- Generate JUnit XML output with --junitxml=reports/junit.xml
- Cache the .pytest_cache directory between CI runs
- Run --tb=short in CI for concise tracebacks; use --tb=long locally
- Split test suites with --dist=loadscope in pytest-xdist for balanced parallel runs

## Documentation
- Write one-line docstrings for non-obvious test scenarios
- Maintain a tests/README.md describing test categories, fixtures, and how to run
- Document custom markers and their intended use in pyproject.toml comments

Remember to leverage pytest's powerful fixture dependency injection and plugin system to keep tests readable, isolated, and fast.
